            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Kaiya Alvarez-Cohen is a tapestry woven from the distinct threads of San Francisco\u2019s working-class immigrant communities. Born in the foggy Outer Richmond to a Japanese mother who was a meticulous housekeeper and a charismatic Mexican-American father who worked as a line cook, Kaiya\u2019s childhood was a flavorful mix of Oaxacan mole and Japanese curry. The hyphen in her name tells a story: \"Alvarez\" from her beloved father, and \"Cohen\" from a marriage that ended in an amicable, if painful, divorce a decade ago, leaving her with her greatest joy, her teenage son, Leo.\n\nHer path was forged in practicality, not privilege. She enrolled in SF State\u2019s Hospitality Management program, dreaming of running a boutique hotel. However, when her father suffered a debilitating injury, Kaiya dropped out to help support her family. She took a job as a hostess at a downtown restaurant and discovered her true calling was in the chaotic, high-stakes ballet of fine dining. She worked her way up with fierce determination: from server to captain, to floor manager, and finally, to her current role as the General Manager of a critically acclaimed restaurant in Hayes Valley.\n\nKaiya\u2019s daily life is a disciplined routine. She leaves her cozy Cole Valley apartment each afternoon, taking the N-Judah streetcar the 2.8 miles to work. The commute is her quiet moment, a time to mentally prepare for the evening\u2019s service. She orchestrates everything from staffing to sourcing ingredients, her management style a blend of her mother\u2019s precision and her father\u2019s warmth. She is the first to arrive and often the last to leave.\n\nThough proud of her career, Kaiya dreams of more. She saves diligently, her sights set on a small, 30-seat restaurant of her own in a quiet neighborhood like Bernal Heights. It would be a place that reflects her soul: a menu fusing Japanese simplicity with the bold flavors of her Mexican heritage. For Kaiya, who has spent her life executing others\u2019 visions, this dream isn\u2019t about wealth; it\u2019s about creating a legacy, a place of her own in the city that shaped her."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nShe remembers being ten, standing on a stool in their foggy Outer Richmond kitchen. The air was a mix of her mother\u2019s steaming rice and her father\u2019s toasted chiles for mole. He\u2019d laugh, showing her how to warm a tortilla on the open flame, while her mother meticulously arranged tsukemono in a small dish. It wasn\u2019t a collision of cultures, but a perfect, comforting harmony. In that moment, she understood that love had a flavor, and it was uniquely hers. This memory became the blueprint for her future restaurant.\n\n2.\nShe was in the library at SF State, buried in a hospitality textbook, when her phone buzzed. Her mother\u2019s voice was thin, trying to be brave about her father\u2019s fall at the restaurant. In that sterile, quiet room, Kaiya\u2019s future split in two. The dream of a degree felt distant and pale against the urgent, visceral need of her family. Closing the book, she knew what she had to do. It wasn't a choice; it was an activation of who she was. Responsibility became her new ambition.\n\n3.\nA year after the divorce, Leo, then six, traced the name \"Cohen\" on the mail. \"Why is your name still Dad's name?\" he asked. The question stung, a phantom limb of her old life. She knelt down, looked into his eyes, and said, \"Because it\u2019s a part of you, and you\u2019re the best part of me.\" In that instant, the name was no longer about a failed marriage. It was a permanent, unbreakable link to her son. It was her anchor in the world.\n\n4.\nThe night she was promoted to General Manager felt surreal. After the last staff member left, the owner handed her a heavy, jangling ring of keys. The cold metal felt impossibly significant in her palm. These were not just keys to a building; they were the validation for a decade of double shifts, missed holidays, and relentless effort. Standing alone in the silent dining room, she wasn't just executing a vision. She was the conductor, and this finely tuned chaos was finally hers to orchestrate.\n\n5.\nIt happened on the N-Judah, rattling home after a grueling Saturday service. As the streetcar emerged from the Sunset Tunnel, the cozy lights of Cole Valley twinkled below. Exhausted, she suddenly pictured it with perfect clarity: a small, warm room in a neighborhood like this. On the menu: karaage with a chipotle-lime aioli; dashi-poached fish over Oaxacan black beans. The vision was so complete, so *right*, that it stole her breath. It wasn't a vague dream anymore. It was the next station on her line."
